1
00:00:05,514 --> 00:00:08,989
I've mentioned before that Wittgenstein

2
00:00:08,989 --> 00:00:11,981
is arguably the greatest linguistic

3
00:00:11,981 --> 00:00:14,926
philosopher of the 20th century.

4
00:00:15,018 --> 00:00:17,795
[The Possibility of God]

5
00:00:18,147 --> 00:00:21,029
Bastard disciple of Bertrand Russell,

6
00:00:21,245 --> 00:00:24,076
who drove Russell crazy

7
00:00:24,599 --> 00:00:27,999
because Russell could not defeat him.

8
00:00:29,623 --> 00:00:32,318
But that Wittgenstein,

9
00:00:33,784 --> 00:00:36,291
he lived above a petrol station in Vienna,

10
00:00:36,291 --> 00:00:37,898
while he's writing his books...

11
00:00:38,527 --> 00:00:41,460
And every day the aroma of coffee

12
00:00:41,460 --> 00:00:43,447
comes wafting upstairs and he's like,

13
00:00:43,447 --> 00:00:45,007
"Aah."

14
00:00:45,007 --> 00:00:46,415
He's smelling that coffee and thinking

15
00:00:46,415 --> 00:00:48,122
"maybe I'll go downstairs and have a cup."

16
00:00:48,779 --> 00:00:52,514
But then one day he had an epiphany and he thought:

17
00:00:53,129 --> 00:00:57,241
"With all of my linguistic power and skill,

18
00:00:58,656 --> 00:01:03,511
I cannot, in words, convey the aroma

19
00:01:03,511 --> 00:01:06,084
of coffee to another person.

20
00:01:06,591 --> 00:01:09,823
I could write a book about it,

21
00:01:09,823 --> 00:01:12,213
but you won't know what it smells like;

22
00:01:12,290 --> 00:01:15,020
you won't get that experience."

23
00:01:15,682 --> 00:01:20,987
So then, people... You could say,

24
00:01:21,525 --> 00:01:24,879
"Then how could dare we say anything about God?"

25
00:01:24,956 --> 00:01:31,751
Yes, that's true, if it's your own speculative conjecture.

26
00:01:33,686 --> 00:01:38,468
Can God – who may have olfactory capacity,

27
00:01:38,468 --> 00:01:41,203
may have the ability to see, hear, taste, touch, smell, feel –

28
00:01:41,849 --> 00:01:45,413
can He express anything about Himself, or not?

29
00:01:46,676 --> 00:01:48,176
That's Guru Maharaj's point:

30
00:01:48,176 --> 00:01:52,520
Can the infinite make Himself known to the finite?

31
00:01:52,920 --> 00:01:55,435
We'll concede: "Yes, good point,

32
00:01:55,435 --> 00:01:59,330
finite cannot know the infinite by finite means."

33
00:01:59,330 --> 00:02:02,382
 

34
00:02:02,382 --> 00:02:04,714
Yes, Rupa Goswami agrees with you.

35
00:02:05,727 --> 00:02:07,991
But that's not the end of the story.

36
00:02:08,590 --> 00:02:11,483
Can the infinite makes itself known to the finite

37
00:02:11,483 --> 00:02:12,944
through infinite means?

38
00:02:13,884 --> 00:02:16,163
Even the most rational person has to admit

39
00:02:16,163 --> 00:02:18,360
that it's possible.

40
00:02:19,405 --> 00:02:22,063
That's why Christopher Hitchens,

41
00:02:22,063 --> 00:02:25,454
the great atheist and writer... His friend,

42
00:02:29,684 --> 00:02:35,161
Martin Amis – as much as Hitchens was an atheist

43
00:02:35,161 --> 00:02:38,380
his friend, who's almost as much as an atheist as him –

44
00:02:38,380 --> 00:02:41,299
said to him: "Chris, you've got to admit,

45
00:02:41,299 --> 00:02:44,016
if, from a purely rational point of view,

46
00:02:44,016 --> 00:02:47,084
there's some possibility, you can't –

47
00:02:47,084 --> 00:02:49,331
you shouldn't eliminate that."

48
00:02:49,331 --> 00:02:51,057
And he said "No! I said there's n..."

49
00:02:51,488 --> 00:02:53,264
Even his best friend said:

50
00:02:53,264 --> 00:02:55,272
"This I'll never agree with you on,

51
00:02:55,272 --> 00:02:58,504
as much as I agree with you, I have to say

52
00:02:58,504 --> 00:03:02,986
that, in the infinite grains of infinite possibility,

53
00:03:03,694 --> 00:03:05,417
it has to be there."

54
00:03:05,801 --> 00:03:07,486
So that's Guru Maharaj's point:

55
00:03:07,486 --> 00:03:10,308
Can the infinite make itself known to the finite?

56
00:03:10,323 --> 00:03:12,238
Then how does He do that?

57
00:03:12,683 --> 00:03:15,434
Amnaya; revealed truth.

58
00:03:15,434 --> 00:03:18,005
It won't be acquired truth based upon

59
00:03:21,203 --> 00:03:26,451
pratyaksha or paroksha: individual experience; collective experience.

60
00:03:28,767 --> 00:03:32,200
It'll be revealed truth, He'll make himself known.

61
00:03:32,400 --> 00:03:38,619
How? Through sadhu, shastra, guru, vaishnav.

62
00:03:38,877 --> 00:03:40,030
Agents.

63
00:03:40,525 --> 00:03:43,254
So what someone needs to tell Wittgenstein

64
00:03:45,161 --> 00:03:47,273
is that, "Yes, you are correct."

65
00:03:47,273 --> 00:03:50,870
 

66
00:03:51,209 --> 00:03:53,614
What to speak of the aroma of coffee,

67
00:03:53,614 --> 00:03:56,693
the name of Krishna, the form of Krishna,

68
00:03:56,693 --> 00:03:59,811
the qualities of Krishna, the pastimes of Krishna,

69
00:03:59,811 --> 00:04:04,279
are beyond the grasp of the mind and intellect.

70
00:04:06,386 --> 00:04:11,458
But, it doesn't mean that Krishna cannot reveal

71
00:04:12,765 --> 00:04:15,985
the name, form, qualities, and pastimes

72
00:04:15,985 --> 00:04:17,954
to the mind and intellect.

73
00:04:18,421 --> 00:04:21,547
Spiritual mind, spiritual intellect.

